post_text:
Good morning Willis ISD families,
We are thankful that our area was not impacted by Hurricane Laura, and we hope that all of your families in other areas are also safe.

Tomorrow, Friday, Aug. 27, will still be a closed school day. We will resume our Phase-In plan on Monday, Aug. 31, as well as remote learning. Thankfully, we have extra minutes built into our calendar therefore we will not need to make up the 2 missed days.

Have a nice long weekend, and we will see you in person or virtually Monday!

post_text:
Willis ISD is actively monitoring the weather for potential impacts to our area. As always, we will take proactive steps as needed to ensure the safety of our students, staff, and community. Please stay safe and heed all weather warnings from local weather experts and officials. We will continue to monitor the weather and provide updates through our mass communication system, the district website and district social media accounts. You can review our weather procedures at the webpage below.

If the district finds it necessary to close for inclement weather, all students will automatically move to Remote Learning for the time schools are closed. The district understands that electrical outages caused by bad weather could impact a student's ability to complete work online. In that case, students would be provided additional time to complete assignments once electricity is restored.

If the district finds it necessary to close for inclement weather, all students will automatically move to Remote Learning for the time schools are closed. In that case, students would be provided additional time to complete assignments once electricity is restored.

post_text:
As the 2020 Football and Volleyball seasons approach, we continue to face challenges due to COVID-19. One of the most impactful requirements for spectators will be the maximum capacity limit for athletic venues, which is currently set at 50%.

There will be a limited amount of tickets available, effective September 1st, 2020; we plan to announce the process for obtaining single game tickets as soon as possible.

Football Note:
As a result of the capacity limits, the UIL has lifted the ban on live streaming high school Friday football games. All games will be available via the Internet. We are in the process of finalizing the method to which we will be streaming our games and will communicate that information in the near future.

We thank you in advance for your understanding in this matter, and we thank you for your continued support for Willis WildKat/LadyKat Athletics.

post_text:
As a part of the National School Lunch Program, some students may be eligible for a free or reduced price lunch. All families wishing to receive free or reduced meals must complete a new application each school year. If the family received assistance in the previous year, it will continue for the first 30 operating days into the new year. The fastest way to apply for free or reduced-price meals is completing an online application. Paper applications can take up to 10 days to process. After the application has been processed, the family will receive a letter stating those benefits for which the family is eligible. If a paper application is needed it can be picked up at any school office, cafeteria or Child Nutrition office.
Learn more here: https://www.willisisd.org/Page/7532

Free & Reduced Meal Price applications for the 2020-2021 school year are now available. Completing an online application ensures faster meal benefits. A new application must be completed each year. Meal benefits from the 2019-20 school year will continue for 30 days after the first day of school or until a new application is processed. Meals will be charged at full price beginning September 28th, unless a new application is completed. Only one application per household needed.

Aplicaciones de comidas gratis oa precio reducido para el año escolar 2020-2021 ya están disponibles. Completar una solicitud en línea se asegura los beneficios de comida rápida. Una nueva aplicación debe ser completada cada año. Los beneficios de comidas desde el año escolar 2019-20 continuarán durante 30 días después del primer día de clases, lo que significa que las comidas se le cobrará el precio completo que comienza el 28 de septiembre, a menos que se complete una nueva solicitud. Sólo una solicitud por hogar es necesario.

https://www.willisisd.org/Page/7532

post_text: See below - let's support our Willis community and help the new owners of the 1097 Newspaper kick off a great first month! Send in your events, classified ads, etc!
shared_text:
Ten Ninety Seven
June 22 at 7:05 PM ·

Good evening to all of our Readers, Followers, and Local Residents. As many of you may already know we are working on getting our first issue out for the month of July.

We are almost 100% complete, but wanted to ask for your help. We are working on a list for the Month of July for our local community events, church events, and library events.

If anyone knows of any events for the month of July that they would like published please let us know any details and we would be glad to add it in.

Also, we are working on a "Classifieds Section" so if you, or someone you know is trying to sell an item/s please get in contact with us in regards to having an ad placed in the paper.

For any questions contact us at 1097newspaper@gmail.com

We look forward to your help. Thanks!

post_text:
Please help us congratulate and welcome our new school administrators for the 2020-21 school year!

Tamara Good, principal of Cannan Elementary for the past four years, will be taking the lead role at Meador Elementary. She replaces Nan Seith who is retiring after many years of service to public education.

Cannan will retain an excellent leader in Kent Copley, current assistant principal, who has been promoted to principal.

Eric Burns, principal of CC Hardy Elementary, has been tapped to lead Lynn Lucas Middle School as principal. He was previously an assistant principal at Brabham Middle School.

Jason Bond, an assistant principal at Willis High School, has been named the new principal of CC Hardy.

Read their welcome messages below.

ATPE - Association of Texas Professional Educators
April 30 at 1:03 PM ·

Meet our April 2020 Volunteer of the Month, Gidget Belinoski-Bailey of Willis ATPE!

Gidget is an educational diagnostician at Roark Early Education Center and Parmley Elementary in Willis ISD. She’s been with Willis ISD for six years—her hometown district—but prior to Willis, Gidget served Spring ISD for 16 years. “I always like mentioning where I worked previously because it is the great educators there that helped shape me into the educator I am today,” Gidget says.

Read her story here: https://www.atpe.org/en/News/ATPE-Blog/2020/April/Introducing-the-April-Volunteer-of-the-Month

REMINDER: Medication retrieval today from 11-1, and again next Tuesday and Wed., May 5-6.

Medication Pick Up:
Due to schools remaining closed, Willis ISD schools will be holding final prescription and over the counter medication retrievals on April 29 and May 5-6 from 11am to 1pm. If you have medicine that you supplied for your child at your child’s clinic, or other medical supplies or belongings that you need to retrieve, it is imperative that you arrange to do so during these times. Medication/items not retrieved by 1pm on May 6 will be disposed of properly per district policy. If none of these dates/times work for you, please contact your campus principal prior to May 6 to make alternate arrangements.

The parent/guardian will need their identification card or driver’s license. If you need to send a designee to pick up the medicine, you must provide them with a hand-written note signed by you, and they will need their ID/driver’s license. Pull up in your car to the front of the school and someone will come to your vehicle. Please do not park and go into the school.

Dear Willis ISD Families,
As a result of the Executive Order issued by Governor Greg Abbott today, the remainder of Willis ISD’s academic year through May 22 will be completed through our current model of distance learning. Updates regarding activities such as graduation will be shared as we learn more from the State.

We understand that this closure presents challenges to each and every household. We remain committed to supporting the health and safety of our students, employees, and community. Our meal distributions will continue through May.

There are a variety of resources available on our website at willisisd.org/onlinelearning, including links to additional learning resources and mental health needs. Please contact your child’s campus if you have questions or needs.

Thank you for your continued support as we navigate these times.

Tim Harkrider, Superintendent

Thank you for your continued support as we navigate these times.

Tim Harkrider, Superintendent

post_text: The Willis Wildkat Wrestling team wrestled at Regionals last weekend (after winning District the prior weekend) in Austin Texas. The boys came away 6th place and qualified 4 wrestlers to compete at State this weekend. Skylar Murillo place 5th in the 138lb weight class. Cameron Collier placed 4th in the 160lb weight class. Josh King placed 3rd in the 170lb weight class. Aiden Collier placed 3rd in the 152lb weight class. Anna Vargas placed 2nd in the 128lb weight class. We are very proud of our Wildkat wrestlers! Wish us luck as we wrestle at the Berry Center in Cypress for a State Championship!

post_text: The AquaKats swam well at the Regional meet in Magnolia a few weeks ago. Diver Blaire Levergne started the scoring by placing 7th in 1 meter diving. The team set four school records at the meet. They were: Sloane Veronico in the 50 free, Kate Mcdowell in 100 back, the girls 200 free relay of Kate Mcdowell, Caroline Taylor, Maci Konen, and Sloane Veronico; and Peyton Sewell who placed 5th in the championship final of the 500 free. Zach Clark made the championship final in the 100 free and placed 8th. The girls 400 free relay of Kate Mcdowell, Caroline Taylor, Maci Konen and Sloane Veronico placed 6th in the championship final. The Team had 4 consolation champions: Kate Mcdowell in 100 back; the girls 200 free relay of Kate Mcdowell, Caroline Taylor, Maci Konen and Sloane Veronico; the boys 200 medley relay of Peyton Sewell, Oliver Bowling, Zach Clark, Bradford Parker; Peyton Sewell in the 200 IM. The girls placed 8th and boys 11th out of 20 teams. Congratulations on a great season!

Lt. Leslee Zemlicka, Willis ISD’s Security Director and a Montgomery County Precinct 1 Constable, has been honored as the first recipient of the BACK THE BLUE award by the Multi-County Crime Stoppers organization.

Lt. Zemlicka was nominated for her hard work and dedication to all of the students and staff of Willis ISD, where she serves as the Director of Campus Security for approximately 7,800 students and 1,000 faculty and staff members.

Thank you Lieutenant Zemlicka for your commitment to provide a safe environment where the students know they can be safe while they relax, grow and learn.
￼
Steve Squier, Coordinator
Multi-County Crime Stoppers

The 24th Annual Willis Kool Kats Chili Cook Off will be February 1, 2020 at the American Legion Hall. Doors will open at 9 am and the silent auction will close at 1 pm.

The Kool Kats need your help to ensure the success of this fundraising event. The money raised helps provide our Special Olympics students with new equipment, uniforms, transportation and entry fees. It also assists the Special Programs department of Willis ISD in educating students with disabilities.

Please consider signing up for a bean or chili team for our cookoff. We also are seeking item donations for our silent auction. Finally, we want to feature YOUR business on our t-shirts! See attached flyers for more information, or contact Casey Buaas or Christie Franz with any questions.

post_text:
Willis ISD Education Foundation board members conducted a district-wide Prize Patrol Tuesday, Dec. 10 and awarded more than $60,000 in grants to Willis ISD teachers! There were cheers and happy tears as one by one, we surprised 32 teachers with a classroom grant. These grants will enhance student learning and brighten their day at the same time!

The Willis ISD Education Foundation is a non-profit, volunteer organization that provides an avenue for business and community members to enhance the education process. The Foundation aims to promote educational excellence and opportunity beyond the scope of the Willis school system by generating financial resources from private funds to provide support for educational programs. Learn more at https://www.willisisd.org/Page/1066. Without your support, these grants would not be possible!

post_text:
Today, an Army STEM Experience Truck visited Willis High School and gave senior students an opportunity to tour the truck and talk to Army recruiters. The truck features a helicopter simulator, a virtual reality roller coaster experience, information on different careers, as well as the technology that supports those jobs.

“Willis High School has built a strong relationship with our military recruiters, and that is why they offered us this opportunity.” said Lori Van Dresar, WHS Counselor and Graduation Advisor. “We are honored that the Army Recruiters chose to bring this amazing government asset to WHS. It’s a great opportunity for our students to learn more about all of the options that await them after graduation.”

We are proud to announce Willis High School’s top ten students for the Class of 2020!

The students are - front row left to right: Vivian Ortiz, Cali Barlow, Peyton Payne, Lily Utecht, Elena Yanez.
Back row: Reece Harkrider, Isabella Sunquist, Grace Hoegemeyer, Sloane Veronico, Cameryn Sebastian.

Principal Stephanie Hodgins stated, “We are so proud of these students for their determination and hard work on academics, while balancing many other demanding activities. Congratulations!"

These rankings are for academic purposes and represent the top spots at the end of the students’ junior year. The rankings are fluid and will not be final for the graduating class of 2020 until five weeks prior to the May 2020 graduation ceremony.

post_text:
The Willis High School Band and Colorguard are on the go with October being competition season. Recently competing in the Friendswood Marching Festival, Galena Park Marching Festival and Lone Star Preview they represented our community very well as they brought home awards in each contest.

- Friendswood Marching Festival - 2nd Place Division 5A &
Caption Award for Outstanding General Effects
- Galena Park Marching Festival - 2nd Place out of 14 bands
- Lone Star Preview - 2nd Place Division 3A,
Caption Award for Outstanding General Effects & Finalist;
placing in the top 10 out of 21 bands

The 183 member organization continues to put all their hard work, sweat and tears into every practice and Friday night half-time show as they prepare for the upcoming UIL Regional and UIL Area Marching contests later this month. Top placements at UIL Area could mean another appearance in the Texas State UIL Marching competition in San Antonio, TX in November. The band is under the Direction of Chris Allen, Andrew Hicks and Colorguard Director, Kaley Baum.

post_text: The use of e-cigarettes, or "vaping," is a rapidly growing and dangerous trend among young people around the country. Willis ISD is launching an anti-vaping initiative to address these concerns with students and parents. We believe that parents and educators have a shared responsibility to shape our children’s future, including educating them about potential dangers and consequences. Superintendent Tim Harkrider released a letter to all parents on Monday, October 7, 2019. You can read the full letter, and access other resources, at our website below.

Linda Roach, reading interventionist teacher at Cannan Elementary, was named the district’s September MVP during the regular board meeting held Monday, Sept. 9. At Cannan, Mrs. Roach works with students in small groups to improve their letter/sound identification, and reading fluency and comprehension. In a special tribute video shown during the meeting, Tamara Good, Principal, said “Many times the things (you) do may seem to go unnoticed, but know this, we see you, and we appreciate you. You are the backbone of this campus now and forevermore.”

Watch the tribute video below.

Willis ISD is forming a committee to discuss a strategic long term plan for the district as our community grows. Committee members must live within the Willis ISD school zone or have children attending a Willis ISD school(s). Consideration will be given to maintaining an equal representation of members from each school in Willis ISD. If you would like to be considered for the committee, please provide us with your contact information on the Google Form linked below by August 19. We anticipate adding 35-40 people to the group. post_text:
Maintenance Department Leadership Changes

Tyler Rhoden has been promoted to Director of Maintenance after serving as Grounds Supervisor for the past five years. He replaces Steve Skyvara who retired in May. Rhoden holds a bachelor’s degree in Horticulture and Crop Sciences from Sam Houston State University. Additionally, Richard Yohner, maintenance supervisor, was promoted to Assistant Maintenance Director. This is a new position that was reclassified from a maintenance supervisor position during the June 10 board of trustees meeting. The new role is needed to lead the district’s growing demands in maintenance projects and construction. Yohner has been with the district 15 years.

Additionally, Richard Yohner, maintenance supervisor, was promoted to Assistant Maintenance Director. This is a new position that was reclassified from a maintenance supervisor position during the June 10 board of trustees meeting. The new role is needed to lead the district’s growing demands in maintenance projects and construction. Yohner has been with the district 15 years.

post_text:
Brabham Middle School Principal Named

Former Dean of Curriculum at Willis High School Richard Ray has been named Principal of Brabham Middle School. Ray was recognized at the board of trustees meeting June 10, 2019. Previously he was an assistant principal in Klein ISD for one year, and the instructor over the Cyfair JROTC for five years. Prior to that he was Superintendent of Professional Military Education Training and Development at Air University in San Antonio. Ray has a Bachelor of Arts in Business Administration from Campbell University in Buies, NC and a Master of Arts in HR Development and Management/Leadership from Webster University in St. Louis, MO. He is currently working on his Doctorate in Education. Ray said, "I am grateful for the opportunity and look forward to serving the students and parents of Brabham."

We are heartbroken to announce that the Willis ISD family has lost a very special person. Sharon Hill Jennette passed away unexpectedly Saturday, June 1, 2019. Sharon retired Friday, May 31, after serving as the assistant to the Superintendent for the last 49 years. Just last week, the Board of Trustees surprised her with the news that they voted to name the future administration building after her. In lieu of flowers, please send donations in Sharon's memory to the Willis ISD Education Foundation, 204 W. Rogers, Willis, Texas 77378.

post_text:
Willis ISD honored two hard working students at the regular Board of Trustee meeting May 13. Mariah Navarro, a third grade student at Parmley Elementary, was named the Elementary Student of the Month. Mariah’s teacher Ms. West said she works hard all the time and is one of the kindest students she has ever had.

Willis High School Principal Stephanie Hodgins introduced sophomore Kelsey Soape as the Secondary Student of the Month, and told how Kelsey single handedly led the effort to sustain a greet students at the door daily effort. post_text:
Two Willis ISD teachers have been selected as two of three finalists in the Association of Texas Professional Educators (ATPE) Charles Pickitt Educator of the Year awards. They are:
Kally Evans, 6th Grade Science Teacher at Lynn Lucas Middle School; and Katrina King, Health Science Teacher at Willis High School. Both teachers are finalists in the secondary category.

The award recognizes ATPE members who demonstrate exceptional or innovative capabilities in their respective educational fields. Winners will be named at the ATPE Annual Summit in July.

Congratulations, and we wish you both all the best!

Willis ISD schools and offices will be closed Friday, May 10 due to heavy rain and flooding predicted for our area. All after school activities for Friday are also canceled. Schools will reopen Monday, May 13 at the normal time. This day will not have to be made up! Have a great weekend, and Happy Mother's Day.

Esperamos que tenga un buen fin de semana, y feliz día de la madre.

post_text:
The Willis High School Varsity Mixed Choir and Varsity Treble Choir competed at UIL last weekend received straight division one or superior ratings from all 6 judges at UIL. The Junior Varsity Treble Choir received straight superior ratings for their concert performance and excellent ratings for sight reading.

Additionally the choir program competed at the Music in the Parks competition in Dallas last weekend earning straight superior ratings, 1st place awards for each choir as well as the best overall choir program award. We are very proud of the standard set and the effort shown by our choir students. Congratulations!
